{{Infobox language |name=Cheke Holo |states=Central [[Solomon Islands]] |region=[[Santa Isabel Island]] |speakers={{sigfig|10,840|3}} |date=1999 |ref=e18 |speakers2=1,500 monolinguals (1999?)<ref name=e15>{{e15|mrn}}</ref><!--both figs appeared 15th ed, so may be same source--> |familycolor=Austronesian |fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] |fam3=[[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]] |fam4=[[Northwest Solomonic languages|Northwest Solomonic]] |fam5=New Georgia – Ysabel |fam6=[[Ysabel languages|Ysabel]] |fam7=East Isabel |iso3=mrn |glotto=chek1238 |glottorefname=Cheke Holo }}
'''Cheke Holo''' (also called Maringe or Mari''n''e, A’ara, Holo, Kubonitu) is an Oceanic language spoken in the [[Solomon Islands]]. Its speakers live on [[Santa Isabel Island]].
== Phonology == The [[phonology]] of Cheke Holo shows some peculiarities, shared with other Santa Isabel languages, like the aspirated stops and the voiceless sonorants. The five-vowel system instead conforms to the prototypical system of the Oceanic area {{harvcol|White|Kokhonigita|Pulomana|1988}}.
