The '''Pan South African Language Board''' ({{lang-af|Pan-Suid-Afrikaanse Taalraad }}, abbreviated '''PanSALB''') is an organization in [[South Africa]] established to promote [[multilingualism]], to develop the [[Languages of South Africa|11 official languages]], and to protect [[Linguistic rights|language rights]] in South Africa. The Board was established in Act 59 of 1995 by the [[Parliament of South Africa]].<ref>{{web cite|title=PanSALB History|url=http://www.pansalb.org/history1.html}}</ref>
In addition to the 11 official languages of South Africa, PanSALB also strives for the development of the [[Khoe languages|Khoe]], [[Khoisan languages|San]], and [[South African Sign Language]].<ref>{{web cite|title=NO. 59 OF 1995: PAN SOUTH AFRICAN LANGUAGE BOARD ACT, 1995.|url=http://www.dac.gov.za/sites/default/files/Legislations%20Files/a59-95.pdf}}</ref>
PanSALB structures include: Provincial Language Committees, the National Language Bodies and the National Lexicography Units.
==Controversy== In January 2016, South African [[Minister of Arts and Culture]], [[Nathi Mthethwa]] dissolved the entire board of PanSALB, after a report that between 2014 and 2015, the board's administrative expenditure had increased from 8 million to 11 million [[South African rand|ZAR]], while the expenditure on its mandate dropped to 17 million from 23 million ZAR, while its irregular expenditure was 28 million. <ref>{{web cite|title=Multilingualism: Pan South African Language Board going nowhere slowly, haemorrhaging millions|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2016-02-25-multilingualism-pan-south-african-language-board-going-nowhere-slowly-haemorrhaging-millions/#.Wk5s01WnFEY|author=Marianne Thamm}}</ref>
